    <li class="google_plusone" target_url="http://about.bnef.com/2009/01/26/carbon-capture-and-storage-long-term-promise-short-term-funding-gap/">
      <g:plusone size="medium" href="http://about.bnef.com/2009/01/26/carbon-capture-and-storage-long-term-promise-short-term-funding-gap/"></g:plusone>
    </li>
</ul>

<script type="text/javascript">
    (function($){
        $(window).bind("load", function() {
            $.getScript('http://platform.twitter.com/widgets.js',function(){});
        });
    }(jQuery));
</script>
</div>
            <div id="story_email"> 
                <a href="mailto:Email?subject=Carbon%20capture%20and%20storage%20%26%238211%3B%20long-term%20promise%2C%20short-term%20funding%20gap&amp;body=http%3A%2F%2Fabout.bnef.com%2F2009%2F01%2F26%2Fcarbon-capture-and-storage-long-term-promise-short-term-funding-gap%2F"><div id="email_story"></div>
                <div class="download_label">EMAIL</div></a>  
            </div>
        </div> 
                
                
        <p>Carbon capture and storage will require substantial additional direct government investment over the next decade if the technology is to play a significant role in curbing global CO2 emissions, according to a new study from clean energy research firm, New Energy Finance. The wide-ranging report analysed 193 operational and planned projects being developed by more than 900 organisations in 28 countries, with a total projected cost of over $53bn. It concluded that carbon capture and storage, or CCS, will reduce global emissions in 2020 by an amount equivalent to much less than 1% of current emissions &#8211; unless further direct support is forthcoming in the short term, and tighter carbon caps in the longer term.</p>
<p>If targets implied by existing cap-and-trade schemes are to be met, New Energy Finance analysis shows that CCS might realistically account for 275MtCO2e in emission reductions by 2020, or 1% of current global emissions. However, of the 193 current and planned projects just 83 involve permanent subsurface injection of CO2 and will account for only 120MtCO2e per year by 2020, less than 45% of the required reductions. Additional direct investment will be needed from governments and corporations to increase the technology’s impact. More aggressive carbon-control programmes around the world, including a sufficiently stringent national cap-and-trade scheme or carbon tax policy in the US will make CCS cost effective in the longer term.</p>
<p>CCS has garnered increasing attention around the world as a potentially significant part of the solution to climate change. Storing or “sequestering” carbon dioxide (CO2) underground or elsewhere prevents it from entering the atmosphere and contributing to the warming of the planet. CCS would also allow coal-rich nations to move closer to energy independence by continuing to use domestic coal rather than relying on foreign, potentially hostile nations for imports of other energy.</p>
<p>Supporters of “clean coal” say that in a future carbon-constrained world, CCS can make coal-to-liquids fuel and other coal-based power generation viable sometime in the relatively near future. Critics charge that CCS is unproven, and worry that supporting it will divert funding from renewable energy and energy efficiency. The New Energy Finance study concludes that CCS is not currently a cost-competitive method for producing low-carbon energy. However, it shows that the costs of the technology can be significantly reduced, and as carbon prices increase over time, it can play a significant role in reducing CO2 emissions, particularly in the period after 2020. </p>
<p>The New Energy Finance study examined each of the major technologies under development and found that while substantial attention is currently given to pre-combustion capture with integrated gasification combined cycle (IGCC) generation as the future of “clean coal,” the industry would do well to shift attention to oxy-combustion, due to the escalating costs and inherent complexity of pre-combustion. If the costs and energy penalties associated with oxygen purification can be reduced over the next 10 years (which is likely), oxy-combustion should prove superior to IGCC owing to its simpler design, potential for smaller plant sizes, and ease of CO2 capture. In addition, along with its potential for use in the next generation of coal plants, oxy-combustion technology can be used to repower many existing post-combustion plants. A rapid shift in focus is needed, however, as 25 integrated power and CCS projects between 2009 and 2020 are planned to use IGCC technology, versus only 13 using oxy-combustion.</p>
<p>“CCS certainly isn’t the answer today for powering the world’s energy system cleanly and efficiently,” said New Energy Finance’s Mark Taylor, one of the report’s authors. “Yet the technology has extraordinary promise. It would be a shame if governments and corporations overlook its potential in the name of meeting short-term clean energy targets.”</p>
<p>Michael Liebreich, chairman and CEO of New Energy Finance, said: “What this report shows is that CCS can indeed play a meaningful part in reducing greenhouse gas emissions, but only in the longer term. To achieve its potential, we need to see approximately a doubling of direct support provided by governments in the short term, and robust carbon cap-and-trade schemes in place for the longer term. In addition, it is unthinkable to approve the construction of any further coal-burning power stations unless their emissions are going to be captured and sequestered.” </p>
<p>Unfortunately, there are no governments that provide sufficient long-term support for CCS, either in terms of direct dollar investment in pilot projects, or in comprehensive carbon-cap programmes that would ensure that CO2 prices were sufficiently high in the near term for the investment required. Europe has gone furthest, approving long-term targets for the EU Emission Trading System and further support for CCS, via bonus allowances worth around EUR 7.5bn.</p>
<p>ABOUT THE NEW ENERGY FINANCE CCS INSIGHT SERVICE:</p>
<p>The New Energy Finance Carbon Capture and Sequestration report was commissioned by eight major international corporations seeking to learn more about the technology and how it can be applied to meet the world’s greatest energy challenges. Following on the heels of the report, New Energy Finance is launching a new CCS Insight Service, which will provide serialised research notes to clients on important and timely topics. The underlying data can be accessed via New Energy Finance’s Desktop Industry Intelligence Service, the largest online database of global new energy companies, projects, and financial transactions.</p>
            
            
                  
                  
                               ABOUT NEW ENERGY FINANCE:

New Energy Finance is the world’s leading independent provider of research to investors in renewable energy, biofuels, low-carbon technologies and the carbon markets. The company’s research staff of over 100 (based in London, Washington, New York, Palo Alto, Beijing, New Delhi, Hyderabad, Tel Aviv, Cape Town, Sao Paulo and Perth) tracks deal flow in venture capital, private equity, M&A, public markets, asset finance and carbon credits around the world.

The New Energy Finance Desktop is the world’s most comprehensive subscription database of investors and investments in clean energy. New Energy Finance’s Insight Services provide deep market analysis to investors in Wind, Solar, Biofuels, Biomass, China, VC/PE, Public Markets and the US. New Energy Finance is co-publisher of the world’s first global stock-market index of quoted clean energy companies, the WilderHill New Energy Global Innovation Index (ticker symbol NEX). The company also undertakes bespoke research and consultancy, and runs senior-level networking events.

ABOUT NEW CARBON FINANCE:

New Carbon Finance, a division of New Energy Finance, is the world’s leading independent provider of analysis, price forecasting, consultancy and risk management services relating to carbon. It has dedicated services for each of the major emerging carbon markets: European, global (Kyoto), Australia and the US, where it covers the planned regional markets as well as potential federal initiatives.

